MATCH_TOOL: Bash
MATCH_PATTERN: \.worktrees/[^/]+/.*((cd packages/shared-types|cd packages/game-cartridges).*npm run build|npm (test|run test|run build)|npx vitest run|vite build)
ADVISORY: |
  Worktree may not have its own node_modules, or its workspace packages may
  have empty `dist/` directories. Two distinct symptoms:

  (a) Runtime drift when tests pass against a parent-repo's stale dist:
      `FactTypes.MY_NEW_TYPE === undefined` at runtime even though source AND
      worktree dist both contain the constant.
  (b) App build fails at import resolution: "Failed to resolve entry for
      package '@pecking-order/auth'" (or any workspace package). Happens when
      running `vite build` / `next build` from apps/* in a fresh worktree —
      the workspace symlink exists but points at an unbuilt dist.

  Diagnose first:
    ls .worktrees/<branch>/node_modules/@pecking-order/shared-types  # missing → resolves to parent
    ls .worktrees/<branch>/packages/auth/dist                         # empty → (b) above

  Fix once at worktree creation — build ALL workspace packages, not just the
  two commonly named ones. `auth`, `ui-kit`, and others all need dist too:
    cd .worktrees/<branch> && npm install
    npx turbo build --filter='./packages/*'

  `turbo --filter='./packages/*'` picks up every workspace package including
  auth, shared-types, game-cartridges, ui-kit, and any future additions —
  prefer this over hand-listing packages (which rots as packages are added).

  After install + packages-build, `apps/<name> && npm run build` resolves
  cleanly. Worktree node_modules contains workspace symlinks back to the
  worktree's own packages — subsequent source edits in those packages
  require another `turbo build` before app tests see them.

  Session costs tracked against this trap:
  - 2026-04-17: ~50k tokens debugging stale shared-types in confessions T4.
  - 2026-04-19: apps/client vite build failed on `@pecking-order/auth` entry
    resolve in the rgba-to-colormix worktree. Fixed with turbo --filter above.
